1
00:00:00,980 --> 00:00:03,440
Hey, Adam, how are you doing today?

2
00:00:03,440 --> 00:00:06,100
I'm well, thanks for having me.

3
00:00:06,100 --> 00:00:06,840
That's good.

4
00:00:06,840 --> 00:00:09,340
So how have you been?

5
00:00:09,340 --> 00:00:13,800
If I recall, a few years ago, you were working on this project called MiVote.

6
00:00:13,800 --> 00:00:19,280
For those who are not familiar, can you do a recap about what MiVote is?

7
00:00:19,700 --> 00:00:26,600
MiVote is a new model of democracy effectively.

8
00:00:26,600 --> 00:00:34,240
It started from an examination of the philosophical ideas of what democracy was meant to deliver.

9
00:00:34,240 --> 00:00:44,900
It then worked through the erosion points that we've endured over time, and then looked at the interventions that could be made to create a purer version of democracy.

10
00:00:44,900 --> 00:01:18,500
And then it spun itself into a technical solution that enables governments, candidates, individual citizens to engage in a genuine conversation that forms policy and sort of takes a frame of reference that the equality of the democracy is not determined by an election, but rather it's determined by the way citizens outline and then decide what policy decisions should be made by their government.

11
00:01:18,500 --> 00:01:19,660
Thanks for the quick rundown.

12
00:01:19,920 --> 00:01:26,940
I think it's also important for me to also talk a bit about designing Open Democracy and its history with MiVote.

13
00:01:26,940 --> 00:01:34,120
The idea behind designing Open Democracy is that it's about bringing people together who are trying to innovate in democracies.

14
00:01:34,420 --> 00:01:43,920
And back then, one of our first gathering in VOTE bring members to your office where you explained about what MiVote is.

15
00:01:43,920 --> 00:01:52,920
So definitely, I would like to know a bit more about your role in this organization as well, as part of MiVote.

16
00:01:52,920 --> 00:01:55,440
Yeah, so I'm the founder of MiVote.

17
00:01:57,760 --> 00:02:01,920
I guess I would describe myself as a democracy activist.

18
00:02:03,220 --> 00:02:13,120
I've been fortunate to be able to talk about the new versions and genuine versions of democracy on four continents with governments all over the world.

19
00:02:13,120 --> 00:02:22,120
I was able to talk about it at Davos, at Stanford, March for Our lives, all over the place.

20
00:02:22,440 --> 00:02:24,500
We started a movement here in Melbourne.

21
00:02:24,500 --> 00:02:30,840
What became clear quickly was that there was international scope for what we were doing.

22
00:02:31,680 --> 00:02:41,520
That was really a lesson that we learned at the Singularity University Grand Global Challenge Awards, where we were finalists in their first ever Grand Global Challenge Awards.

23
00:02:41,520 --> 00:02:59,560
But when we presented and we were talking about a local idea in Melbourne for Australia, not really thinking that anybody else in the world would be interested and we got off the stage and literally were just inundated by nations who wanted to see if they could use our technology and start a chapter in their part of the world.

24
00:02:59,960 --> 00:03:07,720
I think we probably in hindsight grew faster than we should have and tried to do more than we should have with the resource that we had.

25
00:03:07,720 --> 00:03:12,880
But quickly we then had some fairly substantial philanthropic support because we were not for profit.

26
00:03:12,880 --> 00:03:14,800
I see that's quite interesting.

27
00:03:14,800 --> 00:03:23,740
So can you elaborate further on this journey by MiVote as well as the success and the pains that you encountered along the way?

28
00:03:23,740 --> 00:03:27,780
I've also heard that you're also branched along to India and UK as well.

29
00:03:28,480 --> 00:03:30,880
How did this all start it?

30
00:03:30,880 --> 00:03:41,840
If you're going right back to the very, very beginning, I had started thinking about this problem in my last startup business.

31
00:03:41,840 --> 00:03:44,680
So I had several startup businesses.

32
00:03:44,680 --> 00:03:49,220
I was at the point where actually none of them were particularly exciting for me anymore.

33
00:03:49,220 --> 00:03:53,840
I was really becoming increasingly more concerned and aware and engaged with the democracy question.

34
00:03:55,400 --> 00:04:03,600
I made the decision that I was going to leave that business and take some time off, and I wanted to focus thinking about democracy.

35
00:04:03,600 --> 00:04:29,820
So I started interviewing people and talking to religious leaders and political leaders and business leaders and average everyday citizens, first here in Australia and then around the world where I had contacts, just to see whether or not the things that I was identifying as erosion points to democracy were unique to Australia or if they were kind of a more global problem.

36
00:04:29,820 --> 00:04:36,320
At that point, I, by coincidence, met for the first time my co-founder of MiVote.

37
00:04:36,320 --> 00:04:44,720
So we were both at a Cambridge alumni event in Melbourne and as coincidence would have it, I wasn't actually intending to go there because I'm pretty antisocial in general.

38
00:04:44,720 --> 00:04:47,700
I like to be private and kind of keep to myself.

39
00:04:47,700 --> 00:04:53,100
And I was in a meeting around the corner from where that Cambridge event was meant to take place.

40
00:04:53,100 --> 00:04:57,300
And I got a text reminder that said, oh, you know, the thing's on in 15 minutes.

41
00:04:57,300 --> 00:04:59,140
And I thought, oh, fuck, look, I'm here.

42
00:04:59,140 --> 00:05:01,060
It's literally around the corner.

43
00:05:01,060 --> 00:05:04,120
Maybe I'll just stick my head in and see what's going on.

44
00:05:04,120 --> 00:05:14,380
So I walked around the corner and everybody there was about 75 years old, except for one other guy who it turns out was Hamish hughes, my co-founder at MiVote.

45
00:05:14,380 --> 00:05:18,940
And so we spoke to each other primarily because we were the only people of the same age.

46
00:05:18,940 --> 00:05:27,720
And very, very quickly, we learned that we had the same interest and passion for politics and democracy and the way the system worked and leadership.

47
00:05:27,720 --> 00:05:30,900
And then we decided that we would build this thing together.

48
00:05:30,900 --> 00:05:36,320
From there, it became a whole lot of just very grassroots conversations.

49
00:05:36,320 --> 00:05:41,260
So I had said to my wife, I want to hire a couple of cafes in Melbourne.

50
00:05:41,260 --> 00:05:44,320
So my office at that point was in South Melbourne.

51
00:05:44,320 --> 00:05:48,620
It was a very famous coffee shop around the corner, and I was friend of the owner.

52
00:05:48,620 --> 00:05:58,020
I said to him, look, do you mind if before you open the mornings, I open it up for half an hour and just go on social media and invite people to come and have this conversation.

53
00:05:58,020 --> 00:06:04,380
And so I had a few morning coffee sessions where I'd pay for everybody's coffee and they could come in and we could talk about democracy.

54
00:06:04,380 --> 00:06:09,600
And I was sort of at that point, there was no master plan, MiVote wasn't a brand yet.

55
00:06:09,800 --> 00:06:11,880
I didn't have a solution.

56
00:06:11,880 --> 00:06:29,100
What I had done was just recognized that there was some significant erosions to democracy, that I thought that there were interventions for and I wanted to see whether or not I was the only person who was interested in these conversations, or whether or not Hamish and I were kind of sitting on an island on our own.

57
00:06:29,100 --> 00:06:33,540
It turned out pretty quickly, you know, I think the first one we did, we had five or six people turned up.

58
00:06:33,540 --> 00:06:37,580
A couple of weeks later, we had 20 people, and a couple of weeks after that, we had 50 people.

59
00:06:37,920 --> 00:06:40,900
And then we started to think, you know what, we might have something here.

60
00:06:40,900 --> 00:06:43,540
There might be something to this.

61
00:06:43,540 --> 00:06:49,860
Shortly thereafter, a lot of those people became volunteers to start building what would become MiVote.

62
00:06:49,860 --> 00:06:52,480
So at that time, it wasn't called MiVote.

63
00:06:52,480 --> 00:06:55,060
It was originally called Frame Democracy.

64
00:06:56,100 --> 00:07:01,460
And then after Frame Democracy, it became OB4, which was of the people, by the people, for the people.

65
00:07:01,460 --> 00:07:12,580
And then about a year after that, it became MiVote as a brand and as a not-for-profit registered, and you know, it was taking donations and actually building products.

66
00:07:12,580 --> 00:07:16,840
In terms of MiVote, what is the general structure of this group?

67
00:07:16,840 --> 00:07:18,200
How will it work?

68
00:07:18,200 --> 00:07:29,760
I remembered a while ago when you presented in our discussion group, you showed us a visual diagram about how MiVote is intended to operate.

69
00:07:29,760 --> 00:07:33,940
Yeah, I won't go into all the intricacies because it will take the entire hour that we have.

70
00:07:34,640 --> 00:07:52,940
But in essence, what we do is we provide an opportunity for representatives to engage with their citizenry on policy issues, because ultimately democracy is about enacting the will of the people, and you can't enact the people's will if you don't ask the people what they want.

71
00:07:52,940 --> 00:07:53,820
It's not possible.

72
00:07:53,820 --> 00:08:01,920
So if that's the starting premise that says, for me to represent you well, I need to actually know what you want.

73
00:08:01,920 --> 00:08:07,540
What are the tools that we can provide candidates and parties to have that conversation?

74
00:08:07,540 --> 00:08:22,180
Not around elections, not around how can I buy your support, but rather when it comes to climate change, or when it comes to tax reform, or when it comes to domestic violence, or when it comes to putting a fucking tram stop in, what do you want?

75
00:08:22,180 --> 00:08:26,240
What do my constituents want from me, so that I can actually enact your will?

76
00:08:26,240 --> 00:08:34,059
So if you start from that point, which is what we did, you then start to realize that there are influences on being able to do that.

77
00:08:34,059 --> 00:08:41,200
So it's one thing to go out and ask the constituency, then you have to realize that people can buy their way into those outcomes.

78
00:08:41,200 --> 00:08:45,160
So then the influence of money in politics becomes a conversation.

79
00:08:45,160 --> 00:08:48,020
Then the tenure of politicians becomes a conversation.

80
00:08:48,420 --> 00:08:57,720
Then how do you make sure people have an informed voice and an informed vote, rather than they're just voting on the color that they normally vote for, a person that looks nicer to them.

81
00:08:57,720 --> 00:09:00,200
But they actually understand the ramifications of all that.

82
00:09:00,200 --> 00:09:04,200
So anyway, we designed a system that caters for all of that.

83
00:09:04,200 --> 00:09:09,080
The structure of the organization in its early days was fairly kind of fluid.

84
00:09:09,080 --> 00:09:13,540
There was no, it wasn't particularly hierarchical because there was no need for hierarchy.

85
00:09:13,540 --> 00:09:16,260
And in fact, I would say that it's not really hierarchical today, to be honest.

86
00:09:17,320 --> 00:09:23,860
The mistakes that we made were we were probably too open about how everything worked.

87
00:09:23,860 --> 00:09:33,040
And so because we wanted everybody to feel a sense of ownership all the time, it made it very difficult to make decisions because everybody had an opinion and everybody wanted to be heard all the time.

88
00:09:33,040 --> 00:09:36,260
So what is this difficulty you're referring to?

89
00:09:36,260 --> 00:09:38,920
After all, it's been a few years since we caught up.

90
00:09:38,920 --> 00:09:43,220
It's clear you've been trying to open this model up to UK and India as well.

91
00:09:43,600 --> 00:09:46,320
So can you elaborate more on this?

92
00:09:46,960 --> 00:09:48,920
I've spoken about it publicly several times.

93
00:09:48,920 --> 00:09:49,740
It's not a secret.

94
00:09:49,960 --> 00:09:52,780
We decided to spin out the technology company.

95
00:09:52,780 --> 00:09:56,920
So we had originally built the first technology platform in-house.

96
00:09:56,920 --> 00:10:06,020
So in particular, Jamie Skeller worked on building and architecting the first blockchain voting platform in the world, which MiVote created.

97
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:08,680
And so we tested it.

98
00:10:09,660 --> 00:10:11,100
We trialed it in Australia.

99
00:10:11,100 --> 00:10:12,760
We had six votes.

100
00:10:12,760 --> 00:10:18,120
We didn't spend a lot of money to promote them, but by the last vote, we were having four or five thousand people voting on it.

101
00:10:18,120 --> 00:10:19,440
And they were on policy issues.

102
00:10:19,440 --> 00:10:22,420
And the way that we do it is we offer four different choices.

103
00:10:22,420 --> 00:10:24,800
They're not aligned to political party positions.

104
00:10:24,800 --> 00:10:33,260
We take what's called a destinational approach, which means that we ask questions kind of at a higher order than, you know, do you want this piece of legislation or not?

105
00:10:33,360 --> 00:10:37,800
We're kind of sort of talking about which path would you like your government to take?

106
00:10:37,800 --> 00:10:42,100
We provided information packs for each of the four choices for all of those votes.

107
00:10:42,100 --> 00:11:05,600
And what we argued, our contention at the beginning, was that if you offer people multiple choices rather than just the binary, Labour, Liberal, Left, Right, Democrats, Republicans, and you give them four different opportunities, you don't align them to party, you provide them information to understand why all of them, those options, are legitimate and what it means to vote for one of those options.

108
00:11:05,600 --> 00:11:15,360
And then, you don't say to them you can only choose one, you say you can choose as many or as few as you think are in the best interests of your country.

109
00:11:15,360 --> 00:11:18,440
Our argument was, what you'll find is consensus.

110
00:11:18,440 --> 00:11:22,580
You'll be able to build consensus in a highly binary tribal environment.

111
00:11:22,580 --> 00:11:28,400
And everybody that we spoke to said it wasn't possible to do it, and you could never get any significant percentages of support.

112
00:11:28,900 --> 00:11:41,580
We contended in the MiVote model that our constitution requires, that no vote can become policy unless there's 60% voter approval for a particular direction.

113
00:11:41,580 --> 00:11:43,240
And everybody said it wasn't possible to do it.

114
00:11:43,240 --> 00:11:44,780
We ran five or six votes.

115
00:11:44,780 --> 00:11:46,680
We never, ever had less than 60%.

116
00:11:46,920 --> 00:11:50,780
Every vote we ever ran got to a 60% consensus.

117
00:11:50,780 --> 00:11:59,560
And so what we then did was wanted to build a robust technology platform that would allow us to grow significantly.

118
00:11:59,560 --> 00:12:11,040
The mistake that we made that you've asked about was we decided at that point that to build that platform meant MiVote, the political movement would have to become a technology company.

119
00:12:11,040 --> 00:12:13,940
And the board decided we didn't want to do that.

120
00:12:13,940 --> 00:12:20,900
So at that point, we decided to spin out the technology company, which everybody now knows as Horizon State.

121
00:12:20,900 --> 00:12:27,280
We handpicked the three people, one of which was Jamie Skeller, to go and run that technology business.

122
00:12:27,280 --> 00:12:29,060
We didn't own any of it, not 1%.

123
00:12:29,860 --> 00:12:30,980
We didn't sit on the board.

124
00:12:30,980 --> 00:12:32,800
We didn't have a say in how we operate.

125
00:12:32,800 --> 00:12:39,260
However, we did have an agreement that said, we would have to be the primary clients.

126
00:12:39,260 --> 00:12:44,680
So they always had to build for us first, and then for whoever came afterwards.

127
00:12:44,680 --> 00:12:58,080
And a percentage of whatever revenue they earned from the IP that we gave them and the technology that we provided from our first votes had to come back to us as a donation so that we could continue to grow.

128
00:12:58,080 --> 00:13:03,160
They could go out and monetise into the corporate market, into the sports industry, do whatever they want.

129
00:13:03,160 --> 00:13:08,040
As it turned out, it was the single worst commercial decision I've ever made in my life.

130
00:13:08,040 --> 00:13:13,520
So we ended up in a position where they didn't do any of the things that they promised us.

131
00:13:13,520 --> 00:13:17,280
We had very little recourse because we didn't own shares and we weren't on the board.

132
00:13:17,280 --> 00:13:27,060
So we couldn't change what they were doing, but what they were doing ultimately cost MiVote probably five years and hundreds of thousands of dollars in making that mistake.

133
00:13:27,060 --> 00:13:37,940
And where we are now, last four several years, is we have now rebuilt MiVote and included a separate area, which is MiVote technologies.

134
00:13:37,940 --> 00:13:41,640
So rather than spitting it out, we're now building it in-house again.

135
00:13:41,640 --> 00:13:43,100
So it's now integrated?

136
00:13:43,100 --> 00:13:47,960
Yeah, but unlike last time where it was a not-for-profit, MiVote technologies is for-profit.

137
00:13:48,540 --> 00:13:56,500
MiVote, the movement, is not-for-profit, so it remains not-for-profit, but they are effectively part of the same umbrella.

138
00:13:56,520 --> 00:14:00,560
And the whole thing is housed in the United Kingdom, where it's being built.

139
00:14:00,560 --> 00:14:02,860
It's being built in the UK and in England.

140
00:14:02,860 --> 00:14:05,700
We're part of the PEG program out of the UK government.

141
00:14:05,700 --> 00:14:13,020
I don't know if you've heard of it, but we're the first not-for-profit ever to be invited into a place in the PEG program out of the Department of Prime Minister and Cabinet.

142
00:14:13,540 --> 00:14:26,380
And that PEG program invests in international technologies that they see benefit for the UK, and they incentivise them to domicile in the United Kingdom, which is what we do.

143
00:14:26,380 --> 00:14:28,980
Can you elaborate what is PEG?

144
00:14:30,120 --> 00:14:32,080
Like, is that Prime Minister?

145
00:14:32,080 --> 00:14:34,980
No, it's the Entrepreneurs Program out of the UK government.

146
00:14:34,980 --> 00:14:39,000
It's run out of Department of Prime Minister and Cabinet out of the Innovation Council.

147
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:46,620
And what they try and do is incentivise technologies from other countries to move their headquarters to London.

148
00:14:46,620 --> 00:14:48,780
And they give them a whole lot of incentives to do that.

149
00:14:48,780 --> 00:14:49,660
So we did that.

150
00:14:49,660 --> 00:14:51,140
We moved to London.

151
00:14:51,140 --> 00:15:00,480
And Joydeep Mondal, who you might know, Joydeep used to run our Indian office, is now the CEO of MiVote globally, and he runs MiVote Technology.

152
00:15:00,480 --> 00:15:04,160
Is there anything that this whole experience has taught you?

153
00:15:04,160 --> 00:15:13,600
After all, this is 2021 and has been quite an interesting experience for everyone last year as well as this year.

154
00:15:13,600 --> 00:15:30,520
As you can tell, this has been an online interview, even though we planned making this an in-person interview, due to the ongoing lockdown here in Australia as part of the ongoing worldwide pandemic.

155
00:15:30,520 --> 00:15:34,840
So, I imagine this got in you a little bit more introspective.

156
00:15:34,840 --> 00:15:41,060
Has the pandemic influenced your thought on the direction that MiVote should head towards?

157
00:15:41,060 --> 00:15:42,720
I don't think it's the pandemic, actually, Brian.

158
00:15:43,040 --> 00:15:50,680
I think for us Trump's reign was probably the tipping point for us, to be honest.

159
00:15:50,680 --> 00:15:54,580
Because up until that point, we had been talking all over the world.

160
00:15:54,580 --> 00:15:58,060
I think I've been in 100 media interviews on four continents.

161
00:15:58,060 --> 00:16:05,800
And I kept saying, we're edging closer and closer to something that looks like fascism, because people have forgotten what democracy actually means.

162
00:16:06,360 --> 00:16:10,540
And we're measuring the quality of our democracy by the wrong metrics.

163
00:16:11,860 --> 00:16:14,700
And everybody thought I was fucking crazy, right?

164
00:16:14,700 --> 00:16:16,080
And it was all hyperbole.

165
00:16:16,080 --> 00:16:26,620
But then all of a sudden, Trump comes along and a whole lot of critical conventions about the relationship between the governing and the governed started to be peeled away.

166
00:16:26,620 --> 00:16:35,200
And a whole lot of people around the world started going, hey, maybe he's not quite so crazy, because it seems like the things he was saying might be happening here in the US.

167
00:16:35,940 --> 00:16:46,960
And so Trump was the biggest gift to MiVote ever, because a lot of people that were on the fence about whether or not they talked to us came back and started saying, yeah, actually, you know what?

168
00:16:46,960 --> 00:16:53,100
Let's talk about how to make democracy better and stronger and more vibrant and more accountable and more transparent.

169
00:16:53,100 --> 00:17:01,620
And so now, what I can tell you is that MiVote out of the UK is running a series of tests on its new technology.

170
00:17:01,620 --> 00:17:03,020
So the technology is built.

171
00:17:03,020 --> 00:17:04,140
We're testing at the moment.

172
00:17:04,640 --> 00:17:06,800
We'll make an announcement in the not too distant future.

173
00:17:06,800 --> 00:17:23,960
I'm not allowed to say the name yet, but the contract is signed with a member of Federal Parliament in Australia who will be testing and running a series of votes in Australia, in his electorate, over the next six months, as a test and a trial to actually go out to the people and ask them about policy.

174
00:17:23,960 --> 00:17:25,780
But that's one of the ends of the limit.

175
00:17:25,780 --> 00:17:28,800
We're doing the same exact thing with the EU.

176
00:17:28,800 --> 00:17:31,240
We're doing it with some union movements across Europe.

177
00:17:31,720 --> 00:17:35,800
We're doing it with candidates in India.

178
00:17:35,800 --> 00:17:38,560
So we're running a series of trials now.

179
00:17:38,560 --> 00:17:46,060
Those trials will lead us to an IEO, where we're going to offer the product to the market, probably in about six months' time.

180
00:17:46,340 --> 00:17:53,560
And then we'll be open to actually start having a significant effect on government thereafter.

181
00:17:53,560 --> 00:17:54,760
But it's been a long road.

182
00:17:54,760 --> 00:17:56,360
It's been nearly a decade.

183
00:17:57,400 --> 00:18:01,420
In terms of the lessons, there's a tonne of lessons, mate.

184
00:18:01,420 --> 00:18:18,200
You know, walking before you can run, trialling the product at times, having an integrated approach to the relationship between the technology and the charity that works, having people that you can trust who run parts of the business, the movement.

185
00:18:18,200 --> 00:18:19,240
There's so many lessons.

186
00:18:19,440 --> 00:18:20,860
It's been life changing.

187
00:18:20,860 --> 00:18:23,960
Have you seen any other similar projects out there?

188
00:18:23,960 --> 00:18:26,260
And if so, what's your thoughts about it?

189
00:18:26,940 --> 00:18:34,520
Because in this space compared to a couple of years ago, there's a lot more democracy projects propping out these days.

190
00:18:34,520 --> 00:18:47,820
For example, citizen juries, as well as flux party, and voter verifiable paper electronic trails, and voting machines, et cetera, et cetera.

191
00:18:47,820 --> 00:18:51,920
Perhaps there's other projects out there that is of interest to you as well.

192
00:18:53,080 --> 00:18:56,320
To me, the best example of...

193
00:18:56,320 --> 00:18:59,000
Like even though they're not what you agree with specifically.

194
00:18:59,000 --> 00:19:04,000
Yeah, well, so look, it's no surprise, and again, it's no secret that I'm not a big fan of flux.

195
00:19:05,160 --> 00:19:11,780
But what's happening in Taiwan, I think, is probably the best example of citizen-based policy making in the world.

196
00:19:11,780 --> 00:19:12,640
Taiwan.

197
00:19:12,640 --> 00:19:13,140
Yeah.

198
00:19:13,140 --> 00:19:19,920
Although, I would say, even though I think they're doing it best, I still think there are significant flaws with their model.

199
00:19:20,760 --> 00:19:23,540
What is Taiwan doing?

200
00:19:23,540 --> 00:19:27,120
So Taiwan, it's quite extraordinary, actually, what they've been doing.

201
00:19:27,120 --> 00:19:36,740
So they've been going out and building, I would call them citizen assemblies, but they're slightly different, to create new policies.

202
00:19:36,740 --> 00:19:50,740
So the government effectively opens the doors and says, look, for the next month, we're going to focus on a policy related to X, whatever X is, and anyone is welcome to come in and help shape that policy and craft what we're going to do.

203
00:19:50,740 --> 00:19:56,680
And there's a lot of dialogue and there's a lot of two and four between the government and the citizens.

204
00:19:56,680 --> 00:20:01,300
And then they go in and they enact what the citizens design effectively.

205
00:20:01,300 --> 00:20:09,280
What's magnificent about that is that they've already enacted about 150 pieces of legislation that have been crafted by the citizens.

206
00:20:09,280 --> 00:20:12,760
The problem is that it is only the citizens who show up.

207
00:20:12,760 --> 00:20:24,860
And so you're still in the exact same problem that a lot of these models have, which is you're not finding a way to engage the citizenry in any meaningful way in terms of volume, that you can say this is genuinely representative.

208
00:20:24,860 --> 00:20:32,620
So I still think the taiwanese model is flawed, but the design of it is really fantastic, and their outcomes are fabulous.

209
00:20:32,620 --> 00:20:35,120
That's really interesting what Taiwan did.

210
00:20:35,120 --> 00:20:45,320
So I imagine there's a lot we could learn from it, but if they did Composer and Voting like how we did it, what if have helped them model more, in your opinions?

211
00:20:45,320 --> 00:20:47,020
But either way, this is really cool.

212
00:20:47,020 --> 00:20:48,520
Yeah, and I think they might get there.

213
00:20:48,520 --> 00:20:51,820
I mean, again, for them, it's still a trial how it's all working.

214
00:20:51,920 --> 00:21:01,440
I think the opportunity is now to import a whole variety of technological elements, to A, spread the opportunity.

215
00:21:01,440 --> 00:21:18,580
And then, you know, I still have a problem just in general with citizen related votes or conversations that A, relate directly to legislation, because I think most citizens don't understand legislation, nor should they have to understand legislation.

216
00:21:18,580 --> 00:21:21,700
And the other thing is that they are binary conversations.

217
00:21:21,700 --> 00:21:27,200
And I think that's a really dangerous, flawed way to talk about democracy.

218
00:21:27,200 --> 00:21:38,580
And I also think that if we're talking about less tribal outcomes, building more trust, I think we have to increase the threshold dramatically of what constitutes a community decision.

219
00:21:38,580 --> 00:21:49,920
So if you're in a binary conversation, and all you need is 50% plus one person, it's very easy to sway the results of that conversation, that vote.

220
00:21:50,720 --> 00:22:10,520
If all of a sudden you're in a binary, so there's more than two choices, you can vote for as many or as few as you want, and the threshold is now 60%, you can't have policy without 60 or 65 or 70, then all of a sudden, what you're finding is that the community is coming together to say, that's the direction we want to go.

221
00:22:10,520 --> 00:22:15,960
To me, that's a much safer way of building community buy-in.

222
00:22:15,960 --> 00:22:17,800
It builds trust with the representatives.

223
00:22:18,080 --> 00:22:21,720
It becomes much easier to hold people to account.

224
00:22:21,720 --> 00:22:26,500
Everybody can be involved in the conversation, and it's not based upon party ideology.

225
00:22:26,500 --> 00:22:34,160
Right now, we're just stuck in this two-party tribal bullshit situation, because that's what we're used to.

226
00:22:34,160 --> 00:22:37,100
And it's actually making the world worse.

227
00:22:37,100 --> 00:22:40,040
We're not getting any better, we're getting worse.

228
00:22:40,040 --> 00:22:45,740
We have worse climate outcomes, worse domestic violence outcomes, worse immigration outcomes, worse asylum seeker outcomes.

229
00:22:46,200 --> 00:22:53,480
All of the problems that are happening in the world are because of this binary view of the way we look at policy.

230
00:22:53,480 --> 00:22:54,540
I see.

231
00:22:54,540 --> 00:22:57,140
So, what's your current role as well?

232
00:22:57,140 --> 00:23:05,480
Because, like, I remember you're now also working at Spinburn in this new department for innovation.

233
00:23:05,480 --> 00:23:11,020
Is this related to MiVote, or is there a particularly separate role?

234
00:23:11,020 --> 00:23:12,620
No, it's completely unrelated to MiVote.

235
00:23:12,620 --> 00:23:14,860
So my roles at the moment, I wear several hats.

236
00:23:15,060 --> 00:23:18,640
So I'm the global chairman of MiVote and MiVote technologies.

237
00:23:19,780 --> 00:23:24,120
I'm the Director of Global and Strategic Innovation at Spinburn University.

238
00:23:24,140 --> 00:23:28,840
I'm a non-executive director of a technology company called Capsula Tech.

239
00:23:28,840 --> 00:23:37,000
I'm a co-founder and director of a technology skunkworks called Travneer, and I'm an advisor to a whole lot of startups.

240
00:23:37,420 --> 00:23:40,020
So, and, you know, obviously I have five kids as well.

241
00:23:40,020 --> 00:23:41,640
So that's my most important job.

242
00:23:41,640 --> 00:23:42,620
So I've got a few things up.

243
00:23:44,280 --> 00:23:45,940
That's all I've got to do.

244
00:23:46,100 --> 00:23:49,160
I'm really getting there on my book, which is about democracy.

245
00:23:49,160 --> 00:23:52,940
Oh, are you writing a book or reading a book?

246
00:23:52,940 --> 00:23:56,320
You know, I'm writing a book called Mythocracy.

247
00:23:56,320 --> 00:24:09,300
And Mythocracy, the contention is effectively that democracy and politics are mutually exclusive in both philosophy and practice, which is to say that if you are engaged in politics, you will never deliver democracy.

248
00:24:09,820 --> 00:24:13,520
And if you are engaged in democracy, you have no need for politics.

249
00:24:13,520 --> 00:24:19,820
Do you have any particular thoughts on China, America in terms of their political systems?

250
00:24:19,820 --> 00:24:28,980
It seems to me that they're trying to compete in terms of ideology as well as, like, social and culturally, et cetera.

251
00:24:28,980 --> 00:24:31,400
Look, I don't think they're different to any other country.

252
00:24:31,400 --> 00:24:36,920
I mean, I think every country's leaders would argue that their model is, is the model that works for them.

253
00:24:38,860 --> 00:24:45,920
I think, you know, the US are experts at calling themselves a democracy, but they're not a democracy.

254
00:24:45,920 --> 00:24:47,920
In fact, they're a long way from a democracy.

255
00:24:47,920 --> 00:24:49,440
They're a republic.

256
00:24:49,440 --> 00:24:50,420
They don't listen to the people.

257
00:24:50,420 --> 00:24:52,020
The will of the people is irrelevant.

258
00:24:52,020 --> 00:24:58,980
It costs $2 billion to become the president, which is about as undemocratic a proposition as you could find.

259
00:24:58,980 --> 00:25:01,400
The checks and balances don't work.

260
00:25:01,400 --> 00:25:03,920
Very rarely is policy related to what the people want.

261
00:25:03,920 --> 00:25:06,840
So they're not a democracy, but they like to call themselves that.

262
00:25:06,960 --> 00:25:11,460
I think China is in equal measure flawed.

263
00:25:11,460 --> 00:25:20,340
Well, I think it has some concerns about the way that it oppresses minorities and its humanitarian streak.

264
00:25:20,340 --> 00:25:25,740
But at the same time, you can't argue that China has lifted more people out of poverty than any country in history.

265
00:25:25,740 --> 00:25:29,680
So I think all systems have good and bad.

266
00:25:29,680 --> 00:25:30,960
America has good and bad.

267
00:25:30,960 --> 00:25:31,960
China has good and bad.

268
00:25:31,960 --> 00:25:33,440
Everything does.

269
00:25:33,440 --> 00:25:35,420
The problem for me is that none of them are democracy.

270
00:25:35,980 --> 00:25:47,020
And so until we actually enact something that is real in terms of democratic outcomes and democratic process, then we'll never know if democracy is the system that we all need.

271
00:25:47,020 --> 00:25:51,220
But we keep calling what we do democracy and it's not something else.

272
00:25:51,220 --> 00:25:55,720
So how close is Australia to an ideal democracy?

273
00:25:55,720 --> 00:26:00,460
In my own personal opinion, there's still a lot wrong with Australia's democracy.

274
00:26:00,460 --> 00:26:05,540
But in some ways, we're still comparatively better than many other countries out there as well.

275
00:26:05,540 --> 00:26:07,020
In certain aspects.

276
00:26:07,220 --> 00:26:13,580
I think, look, I think Australia has better outcomes because ultimately we have a smaller population to deal with it.

277
00:26:13,580 --> 00:26:15,420
So it's more manageable.

278
00:26:15,540 --> 00:26:20,080
I think our success is by default, not by design, to be honest.

279
00:26:20,220 --> 00:26:20,700
I would argue...

280
00:26:20,700 --> 00:26:22,420
The lucky country?

281
00:26:22,420 --> 00:26:24,120
Yeah, well, maybe.

282
00:26:24,120 --> 00:26:26,060
I think our luck might be running out.

283
00:26:26,240 --> 00:26:33,260
I would argue that the Morrison government is basically a fascist government.

284
00:26:33,260 --> 00:26:37,340
And so it has no interest in listening to the citizens.

285
00:26:37,340 --> 00:26:38,920
It's controlled by media interests.

286
00:26:38,920 --> 00:26:41,000
It's controlled by the Minerals Council.

287
00:26:42,780 --> 00:26:50,920
It has a neoliberal approach to every problem, which is why Sydney wouldn't lock down for ages because business always has to win.

288
00:26:50,920 --> 00:26:51,600
It's...

289
00:26:51,600 --> 00:27:02,840
You know, if you look at the last election alone, you have a situation where you had somebody who spent $87 million to try and swing the outcome of an election in Queensland.

290
00:27:02,840 --> 00:27:13,420
You had a situation where the Australian Electoral Commission themselves identified over 70 breaches of electoral law, but they don't have any power to do anything about those breaches.

291
00:27:13,420 --> 00:27:16,560
Yeah, I mean, we have fundamental problems in this country.

292
00:27:16,700 --> 00:27:26,200
And yes, we're the lucky country because most of the time the weather is good and most of the time the lifestyle is good and we've got great coffee and people feel like they have some freedom, but it's not a democracy.

293
00:27:26,320 --> 00:27:28,720
It's a bloody long way from a democracy.

294
00:27:28,720 --> 00:27:36,520
Thank you very much for your thoughts and views about the current state of the run and pathways towards democracy.

295
00:27:36,520 --> 00:27:39,260
At this point, we should probably start wrapping up.

296
00:27:39,260 --> 00:27:44,900
And I really appreciate your time taken to spend your time to be interviewed.

297
00:27:44,900 --> 00:27:47,060
We should start closing up this interview.

298
00:27:47,060 --> 00:27:51,560
So how can people help you after MiVote is still going?

299
00:27:51,560 --> 00:27:57,320
And I'm sure you're still growing the organizations and want to bring it further.

300
00:27:57,320 --> 00:27:57,800
Yeah, it is.

301
00:27:57,800 --> 00:28:03,960
Look, you can go to myvote.tech, which is the website, and you can sort of look at what we're doing there and keep involved.

302
00:28:03,960 --> 00:28:10,800
Reach out to the team in the UK and India if you want to get involved, if you want to learn more, if you want to be part of what we're doing there.

303
00:28:10,800 --> 00:28:13,420
We're doing some really interesting work here with the tests.

304
00:28:13,420 --> 00:28:17,460
We're doing some really interesting work in the EU.

305
00:28:17,460 --> 00:28:22,300
You know, for people who are committed to this space, as you are, Brian, I know you are and I am as well.

306
00:28:22,580 --> 00:28:26,180
There's lots of stuff to get you to roll your sleeves up and get your hands dirty with.

307
00:28:26,180 --> 00:28:27,180
But thanks for having me.

308
00:28:27,180 --> 00:28:28,680
I appreciated the opportunity.

309
00:28:28,680 --> 00:28:29,560
Not a problem.

310
00:28:29,560 --> 00:28:32,340
Thanks so long for coming along to this interview.

311
00:28:32,340 --> 00:28:33,240
Cheers.

312
00:28:33,240 --> 00:28:33,460
Thanks.
